Last week I added a letter formation station to our kindergarten hallway, and I got to share it with our kindergarten team on Friday! This is an idea that @hollyehle shared from her school, and I fell in love! Students walk down the hallway and practice letter formation with their fingers as they say the letter, sound, and trace the letter! It can also be used as a brain break station for students who need a movement break. 
 
Our intervention teacher walks a group of first graders to her room each day for a Fundations lesson, so she started having them walk through the letter formation station on their way! Here’s a super FUN way to practice segmenting and blending phonemes! Segment a word and say each phoneme slowly for the student. The student will repeat the phonemes back to you and pop each sound. Prompt the student to blend the sounds together and say the word smoothly as they spin the fidget! It’s a great tactile and visual addition for segmenting and blending! If students are still struggling to blend, remember to start with continuous sounds. Continuous sounds are sounds with a continuous flow from the mouth or nose. (They can be held out such as /m/ and /o/.

This reminder post is for every teacher, and in particular, for new teachers in the profession! ☺️ Here are three important things that I have always focused on during those first few days back from winter break:
 
1️⃣ Rules, Routines, Procedures - It’s so important to spend time reviewing, modeling, and practicing your routines and procedures, just like you did that first week of school. If, as an adult, you struggle to get back into routine and the groove of things after a break, then guess what? So do our kids. 😉 Focusing on your routines again will make the last half of your year run so much smoother, and helps everyone feel successful! ☺️

2️⃣ Social Emotional Support - A lot of kids are coming back into our classrooms with heavy hearts. Breaks from school are not always easy for all kids. For some kids, they may have experienced some sad, frustrating, or even traumatic things over the past couple of weeks. Make it a big deal to see them again and let them feel that warmth and love that they need to from you and your classroom family. ❤️
 
3️⃣ White Space - Build some intentional white space into your lesson plans. Kids will want to talk to each other and reconnect with friends- and with you! ☺️ Embrace it and carve time out for it. By giving them the space and time to chat and reconnect, you’ll feel less stress or frustration because it can happen during a planned time in the morning, and not during instructional time. Let them be little and reconnect with their friends. 🥰💕 
 
Do you focus on any (or all) of the above during your first week back? I hope these little reminders were helpful! I also have a blog post that goes into even more tips for the first few days back from break, if you’d like to read more. Click the link in my profile, or go to http://bit.ly/afterwinterbreak

We reviewed the concept of open and closed syllables today using my office door! Open the door and these one syllable words are open. The vowel can “run out the door” because nothing is closing it in, so it makes its long vowel sound. Close the door and a consonant appears, shutting the vowel in and making it say its short sound. 
 
My OG kiddo loved this concrete, hands-on practice and review today! Have you used an actual door opening and closing to practice open/closed syllables yet?🥰

Today I worked on the -ed suffix with a second grader. Placing a dot under the last sound of the base word helped him identify whether that last sound was voiced or unvoiced so that he could read which sound of -ed the suffix made. 🥰 He did a great job! We’ve added only one sound of -ed each time. If you have students struggling with suffixes, the last thing you want to do is introduce all three sounds of -ed in one lesson. 💜 That will get really confusing to a-lot of kiddos. Remember to be explicit, direct, and systematic by teaching one sound at a time. 🥰 
 
Need a refresher on the -ed suffix?
▪️ If the base word ends in a voiced sound, the -ed suffix makes the /d/ sound. Example: filled
▪️ If the base word ends in a unvoiced sound, the -ed suffix makes the /t/ sound. Example: missed
▪️ If the base word ends in a /d/ or /t/, sound, the -ed suffix makes the /id/ sound. Example: melted (*dialect can sometimes make this last one be pronounced with a short e sound)

🧠 DID YOU KNOW….Orthographic mapping is NOT an activity? It’s not a skill. Orthographic mapping is a mental process. There are things we can do to promote the PROCESS of orthographic mapping, but it’s important to be aware that we cannot say things like, “We are doing orthographic mapping by completing this worksheet.” That’s not how this process works. 😉
 
Orthographic mapping is the process used to permanently store words into our long-term memory. In order to promote this mental process, we can help students break the pronunciation of a known word into its individual phonemes. Then, the individual phonemes are connected to the correct graphemes (letters). The pronunciation of the word, the word’s meaning, and the letter sequence of the word’s spelling gets bonded together during orthographic mapping. 
 
While we cannot “teach” orthographic mapping, we can help students connect phonemes to graphemes through mapping mats such as the ones in this picture! Saying the word, breaking it into its individual sound parts, and connecting each phoneme to the letter(s) used to represent it can promote phonemic awareness and phonics skills, which need to be in place for orthographic mapping to happen. 😀

When students are slow to retrieve letter sounds, sounding out a word becomes more difficult and labored. When readers have a strong understanding and foundation of sound-symbol relationships, decoding words becomes easier and more automatic. By practicing the sounds that graphemes make in daily drills, students improve their ability to quickly identify and produce the letter sounds and patterns automatically. In turn, this increases word recognition skills and their abilities to blend sounds together quickly, accurately, and smoothly.

Who would’ve thought that fast forward three years, the education profession as a whole would now be utterly comfortable and confident in this world of remote learning when necessary? They say that if you truly love your job, it’ll never feel like work. I felt that quote deeply this year. Today was the last day of school, and this card that I found on my desk was everything I didn’t know I needed. Leaving my classroom after 12 years, and beginning a coaching position was scary, exciting, and nerve-wrecking. I made a lot of mistakes. I sent too many emails at times. There were plenty of questions that I didn’t have answers to. There were times when our state department or an outside source didn’t have the information we needed, so I looked like I had no idea what I was doing. Sometimes, I just flat out didn’t know what I was doing. 🥴🤷🏻‍♀️
 
And I learned that’s okay. Because this isn’t about doing it perfectly. It’s about sitting beside teachers and saying, “This feels messy and uncomfortable. Let’s figure it out together.” ❤️ It’s about encouraging teachers to ask for help. It’s about saying, “Hey- this isn’t working. Can you observe this kid and see if you notice something I’m not?” And in those collaborative coaching moments, magical things start to happen. Students grow. Teachers grow and gain confidence. They realize they don’t have to do this on their own. I’m so thankful for the teachers I worked with this year who held their doors and hearts open. I’m grateful for the ones who extended grace and encouragement as I learned how to navigate a new role. 
 
This year felt hard, but it had accomplishments, too. We adopted a new foundational K-2 program (UFLI) that teachers and students are excelling at. We literally threw away F&P boxes and started using a reliable universal screening and progress monitoring system (Acadience). We developed vertical, streamlined curriculum maps for PreK-5. We have explicit writing instruction taking place in all classrooms using The Writing Revolution approach. The future is BRIGHT for our students and our building, and I’m grateful to have a tiny role in what lies ahead for our kids. 💙
 
Self-reflection is key to consistent growth and improvement. What went well this year? What didn’t? Share with us below! ❤️

Let’s talk about the words do and go, and help our students understand why we add an es to get the words does and goes. Want an instructional challenge today? Tally how many times you, as the teacher, are providing the direct, explicit teaching and modeling of the concept. It’s easy to think that telling students and showing them one or two times is enough before we move on to doing it together, but it is imperative that the I DO part of your teaching is not cut short or de-emphasized. Try these self-prompts to get more I DO’s into your lesson before gradual release:
▪️ “Watch as I ____.”
▪️ “My turn. Eyes on me.”
▪️”Watch and listen to me blend this word.”
▪️”This word, _____, means ____.”
▪️”Watch me do that again. My turn.”
 
Introducing a new vocabulary word? Instead of, “What do you think this word means? Does anyone know what this word means?” Direct instruction for I DO sounds like this: “This word is ____. It means _____. An example would be _____. Listen to me use this word in a sentence: “_______.”
 
As adults, we often need to watch and see things more than once before we can do it ourselves. Our students are absolutely no different. If they aren’t mastering a concept the way you had hoped, go back to the I do. Model, model, model. 
 
I do. I do. I do. (and sometimes more I do!) BEFORE we move to We do. ❤️

What is the scooping method? We can work on phrasing, or smoothly grouping words together into meaningful phrases, to help students increase fluency skills. This helps to develop the natural rhythm that makes oral reading sound similar to conversational speaking when it comes to rate and intonation. Reading with appropriate phrasing also helps with comprehension.  Pre-scooping the text provides a model for the student. Have the student scoop up the phrase with his or her finger while reading, by tracing over your scooped lines. Read the sentence or page twice so that the student can practice the phrasing. How do you teach text features? Before embarking on my science of reading journey, I would spend an entire week or two focusing solely on nonfiction text features. 🙈 It was like it was its own “unit”. 🥴🙈 (Know better, do better right?!) Here’s what we can do instead:
 
🟢 Embed the exposure and attention to text features throughout the entire year, with every book you read aloud. “This book has a caption! I’m going to read what it says. It’s right under this picture, and it tells me more about the photo!”
 
🟢 Read ALOT of informational read alouds to your students. 
 
🟢 Point text features out whenever you see them. 
 
🟢Use text features to teach background knowledge, and direct their attention to the feature and its purpose. 
 
🟢Ask questions during your read alouds or lessons that require students to USE the feature!
 
🟢 Embed text features into your writing. If you’re learning about penguins, write about penguins by writing captions for various photographs. Create a table of contents for a book about penguins based on all of the details you learned (great for determining importance). Expand a sentence that is based off of a graph or chart found within the penguin book. 
 
🟢 Teaching nonfiction text features in isolation will not transfer the way we wish, were originally trained, or intend it to. Just as we can’t practice all the graphemes for the /j/ sound for a week and expect students to use it accurately and consistently for the rest of their lives, it doesn’t happen with text features either. 🤍 Do you agree? Are there any ideas listed above that you’re going to try out? Share with us below!

What is the difference between closed and open word sorts? Unlike a closed word sort, the teacher does not provide the categories (ex: phonics patterns) to the students to use during the sort. In an open word sort, such as the one shown in this video, the students work to discuss the words and sort them based on specific features they decide on. In this clip, the students decided to sort the words based on the vowel sound: short or long. (Notice how they did a great job helping to each other that the e in the word “have” is there because no word in the English language ends in a v. 👏) 
 
I LOVE using open word sorts at the small group table! It’s a great way to build critical thinking, creativity, and communication! Do you use open word sorts with your students? 🥰
